            <Title>Sight Spot</Title>
            <Text>Finding Elrahet was easy because that witch never moved far from where she sat down, and that morning Seb had seen her sit down at the ambush sight spot. Getting up to her, however, was difficult. Seb could either climb up the steep cliff face, or she could take the long way around. Since she had to carry the bones she took the long way. She found the Junei road and walked it up into the mouth of the Junei pass. Instead of following that road through the mountains and all the way south to Meskalim, she scrambled off onto a smuggler’s trail which snaked up towards the mountain peaks. Before long, she hopped off that trail to follow a path which Ayram had made, one which double-backed towards the east.
It was nearing mid-day when Seb made it to the that wide, mid-cliff ledge where Elrahet was sitting. As far as ambush sight spots go, it was perfect—it offered a privileged view of everything east of the Hias mountains. Below was the mouth of the Junei Pass, out of which the Junei road poured. This unkempt road meandered down into the dark Junei hills, where it was dissected into a filigree of footpaths that wiggled down into valleys and bent around black screes and outcrops of solid rock before shooting through the ravines and bowing along the bottoms of wide, long-dried washes before emptying out, at last, into the Junei plain. Once out on the plain, all roads got lost because there the white ground is a rocky caliche that gets swept clean by the strong northerly Junsi wind.
Elrahet was alone up on that high ledge. To Seb’s blurry eyes, she was nothing but a bundle of black rags and long smoky hair flowing out the front of an old crone’s hood. She was sitting cross-legged and looked like she was communing with the vastness of the world, but really, she was sitting, watching, and waiting for their prey to rumble along.
“Took you long enough,” the witch mumbled as Seb approached.
Seb didn’t wait to catch her own breath before saying, “Gugi found some bones and—”
“I know.” 
Seb wondered how the witch knew, because the old woman hadn’t yet turned her head to see what Seb was carrying. But of course, this was, after all, the sight spot, and it had a good angle on every ravine, and on top of that, Elrahet was a witch. Who knows how far her witchy eyes could see.
“Bring them here,” Elrahet said.
Seb knew witches were cantankerous creatures, but Elrahet was especially cantankerous. Seb wondered about her age, though numbered age was rarely a thing people of the Sand tracked. A sand dune has no age, and outland witches like Elrahet were just as elemental. Her features were as dark, sharp, and solemn as any slab of sand-bitten stone. Her sun-drenched skin was as brown and leathered as the wrinkly bark of any pepperwood tree. Her layers and layers of black-rag robe pillowed her knobbly frame and made her look a bit like a diseased crow. Elrahet was as much a native creature of the Sand as the Hias mountains themselves, and probably as old.
“Should I command your every twitch?” Elrahet snipped. “Put the bag down.”
Seb set the bag of bones down gently, not wanting to annoy the woman. She didn’t want to be shooed away before she’d heard any new witchy words. It was her great mission in life to listen when Elrahet spoke. This was a difficult mission, because not only did Elrahet harbor disdain for folks in general, she hated Seb more than most. And why shouldn’t she? As a witch above witches, Elrahet could see the plan. She knew what Seb was. And to make Seb’s quest more difficult, when Elrahet did speak, she spoke softly, hoarsely. Her throat croaked like a dying man. All her sentiments were brusque and rude. All her sentences were death sentences. 
Then there was her bloodspeech. That’s what Seb called Elrahet’s absent-minded mumbling. She called it bloodspeech because whenever the old crone spoke it, Seb’s own blood tingled, and as soon as the bag of bones was opened that bloodspeech was flowing. Elrahet reached in, bone by bone, gave it a once over, then tossed it over the cliff. Eventually she stopped, looked up at Seb and through her irascible sneer she growled,“Busy yourself.”
Seb stepped back and privately cursed herself for not handling the situation with more tact. She should have expected less. Elrahet was impossible to please. In the first few months of Seb’s journey with the Ayramun, she’d tried winning the witch over with kindness—she’d make her meals, wash her blankets, carry her things, and for all that, Elrahet called her a ‘servile goat’. If Seb ignored the woman entirely, that only enraged her. If Seb did what she wanted, exactly how she wanted it, no more or no less, then she was a ‘mindless poke’. It had been three whole years and as many months, and Seb had learned almost nothing about Elrahet’s peculiar brand of witchery.
The only bit of wisdom she’d ever heard her speak was a rather childish aphorism given to young Papi. Papi had been pouting about some useless thing and Elrahet said to him, “Every weakness is a strength, and every strength, a weakness.” If anyone else had said something as stupid as that, Seb would have disregarded it. Strength is strength. Weakness is weakness. Seb’s eyes were a weakness. If a thing was up close she could keep it sharp, but ‘way far out’ and ‘not too far off’ were smashed together into a blurry haze he called ‘out there somewhere’. She looked out on the Junei plain from that high ledge, and all she saw was a wash of white ground underneath a blur of blue sky.
The only good thing that came of her unreliable eyes was that she never had to stand watch, and while she took special pleasure in not being saddled with that chore, calling that a strength was merely twisting words. When a woman is strong she doesn’t need to twist words. For a witch steeped in the mysteries of the Spark to say a thing like that, to say ‘weakness is a strength’, then there had to be some deeper purpose underneath the surface. Elrahet only ever spoke to bend the world to her will. Her words might have been for Papi, but Seb had overheard it, and her overhearing it was no doubt as much a part of Elrahet’s intentions as if she’d heard the words directly. Elrahet was sending her down a path. Seb was sure of it.
Seb stared out at the Junei plain and tried to find the coming caravan by its aura. She knew the caravan was out there somewhere in that blur, making its way towards the pass to be set upon by the Ayramun. She let her eyes cross just enough so that the white landscape doubled and blurred until the edge between the white chaliche and the blue of the midday sky softened into a clean gradient. She strained under the effort, until, at last, there was nothing else in the world but her, that cloud of color, and the distant caravan—if indeed it was even there. She supposed it was there, and she hoped to see its aura flare. Maybe it takes bad eyes to see the divine light of purpose that shines out of every living being. Maybe that’s how her weakness was a strength.
She stared into that blur and bore the look of a woman possessed—jaw clenched tight, breathing in sips, skin tingling, stomach tense. She could feel the energy screaming out of her eyes, she was scouring all the world with it. She trembled as the gods trembled. Sweat beaded on her brow. 
Then she caught a faint whiff of a curious odor. A foul odor. Was it Elrahet’s? Was it her own?
She took another sniff and was hit with a familiar musk—it was hers.
And there were some nesting brightbeaks, up on the cliff behind. Seb knew this without looking because when brightbeaks jump out of their holes they flap their little wings so hard that they beat a pathetic, warbling whistle out of their tiny chests. One flew right by her ear.
But that brightbeak wasn’t the most distracting thing. That honor went to the way in which the borcandi juice oozed out of the spine tucked in her cheek and welled up in her mouth. Borcandi juice doesn’t play nice with the stomach, so people spit it out. But spitting would break her concentration. Then again, her concentration was already broken, so she spat—she spat out  the whole damn wad. It was as big as her tongue.
“Dammit, Seb! You’re a servant of Shis, I swear it!”
Elrahet’s accusation sent Seb into a flustered panic. A long thin track of green-gray spit lacing across the bag of bones. Thankfully, none of it had touched Elrahet.
“Aw, shit! Sorry! Shit. Didn’t mean to.”
She crouched down and tried to atone for her absent-mindedness by wiping the bag clean with her dirty sleeve.
“Get away afore I have you tossed off the cliff!”
“Didn’t mean it.”
Elrahet picked up her short, gnarled root of a walking cane and swung it at Seb’s head. Seb pulled back in time to watch it brush her nose.
Elrahet glowered and said, “I’m that close to cursing your flesh so it steams your bones.”
“I didn’t mean it. Here, let me—”
Elrahet swung again, and her backswing was faster, so fast that the cane head smacked Seb’s cheek. If the old woman had been serious, it might have broken Seb’s face.
Seb clutched her bruised cheek and stumbled back, thankful it was only a warning, though Elrahet’s withering glare said her patience would not bear another word. 
Seb cursed herself again as she trudged away. This was another of her many weaknesses—she was forgetful. She couldn’t hold onto a moment if she were alone in a pitch-black cave. People said this was because of all the spines she chewed, but Seb knew that wasn’t true because she’d always been like this. And she’d never once been in a position where her fitful mind was a strength. Gugi had said that if her mind was always jumping around then at least that means she can’t be sad for too long, and so she should be happy about that, but somehow that wasn’t true—being sad was the one thing Seb could be for too long.
She leaned over the cliff face and spat a fat loogie down. She watched it fall with some delight, though she was denied the pleasure of seeing it splat on the rocks below because the ground was far enough away to be ‘out there somewhere’.
That’s when Moto came scrambling down to the sight spot from some hidden perch up above.
Seb disliked Moto. Moto, a black man from Zos, was stronger, younger, and more skilled than Seb in every way imaginable. He was too well put together to be an Ayramun. Everyone else made do with dark, patchwork robes and nail-strapped soles for shoes, whereas Moto had silver metal buckles on his dusty black boots, and he wore an orange robe that was tucked and folded into sharp knife pleats that slanted across his chest and were kept secured by a wide and tight black sash around the belly. Moto was so clean and fastidious that he would have been at home in the upper echelon of Hrkan society. He even had a sword, a long, curved sword set inside a gold-studded scabbard. It even had a name. Worse than all of this, he had healthy teeth. Few things made Seb more aware of her own disgusting self than being in the presence of healthy teeth. A woman is hard done up when a smile does nothing but make her jealous.
Moto surveyed the Junei plain and said to Seb, “You can’t see them, can you?”
The bastard knew she couldn’t see shit. That’s who Moto was—there was a bag of dead bones not ten feet away, an ill omen just discovered, yet here Moto was taking the time to take the spit right out of Seb’s cheek.
“Course I can’t see,” said Seb, and Moto chuckled. His was a damned hearty, healthy chuckle.
“Well they’re there,” he said. “They’re on their way. Exciting, isn’t it?” He then looked down at Elrahet, pretending to notice the bones for the first time. “And who is that?”
Loath to be interrupted, Elrahet grumbled out a barely-audible, “Nothing.”
“Nothing? What does that mean?”
“Means what it means.”
“I need to know. The Mazid will be here before long. Do these bones change things?”
Elrahet stood up, grabbed the bag, and tossed it over the edge of the cliff. As the bag fell, the bones came tumbling out, cracking against the cliff face.
Elrahet turned and glared at the two pokes. Her skin was so lined with age that even the subtlest action of her brow would send it cracking into sharp relief. At the moment there was only the faintest hint of her familiar sneer. Then she huffed and shuffled down the ridge path, leaving Seb and Moto to wonder at the meaning of her sudden leaving.
“I guess that means they don’t matter,” Moto mused. “And I guess that means it’s on.”
“You sure they’re out there?” Seb asked.
Moto nodded and pointed out towards the blur. “There’s a tiny black speck and a faint cloud of dust. That would be them. That would be our target.”
“You sure that’s them?”
“Who else could it be?”
“Could be anyone.”
Moto snorted in annoyance, which was a common enough occurrence that some of the Ayramun called him a ‘rutting bull’, though they were careful to never let Moto overhear.
“Elrahet predicted that a Mazid and his Minder would be making for the pass,” he said. “And that the two would be hiding themselves in a blackwood caravan. She said they’d be coming mid-day today.” Moto pointed out to the desert again, this time with two imploring hands. “There’s a caravan out there. It’s mid-day. It all fits. That’s who we’re hunting. Or do you doubt Elrahet?”
Seb spat another loogie off the cliff. “Did Elrahet say anythin’ about a dead body?”
“No,” Moto said defensively. “Are you saying something about a dead body?”
“I’m not sayin’ nothin’, I’m lookin’ at it scattered all over these hills.”
“I don’t see why it changes anything.”
“If there’s a curse floatin’ in them hills, then Ayram should know about it.”
“Who said anything about a curse?”
“What else is a bag of bones supposed to be?”
Moto snorted again. “Everything is a curse to you. A rock stuck in your shoe is a curse. A dead leaf is a foul omen. Unless Elrahet thinks there’s something more here, then it doesn’t change anything.”
“How’s it not change nothin’? How’s findin’ a dead body not put a notch in your bow?”
“Because I’m a man of resolve, Seb. I go until the goings no good.”
“You don’t even know for sure that there’s a Mazid out there in that desert. Could be only merchants and we come out here for nothin’.”
“If it’s only merchants, then we knock off a few fat bellies and we get a little richer. What’s the problem?”
“Could be that those aren’t merchants, but a bunch of Hrkan Skulsi in disguise.”
“A few soldiers won’t change the balance.”
“What if it’s more'n a few?”
“Then we’ll kill more than a few.”
“And how many is that?”
Moto sighed and pulled a small, red leather purse out from the belly of his robe. Seb’s eyes went wide at sight of it, for inside that pouch was a ribbon of black silk, and folded inside that silk were two smooth rock crystal lenses set inside thick brass rings. These rings were joined together by a dangling chain that, when stretched, was the length of Moto’s forearm. Seb always itched to try out those lenses, but Moto never let her touch them. Seb hated Moto for that. If those two lenses, set in array, could magnify the distance and make the horizon seeable, well, Seb wanted to have a look.
Moto sat down on the edge of the cliff and propped his elbow up on one knee and let his other leg dangle free. He hunched over, put the smaller lens up to his eye, then stretched out the other lens as far the chain would let, and began his squinting study of the distant blur.
Seb didn’t appreciate Moto sitting that way. It wasn’t just the lenses, it was the casual disregard for what Seb was capable of doing. In a flash, Seb could be right behind the man and push him off the cliff. Seb could end him right there. For all of Moto’s strength and skill with a sword, Seb could end him here. There were plenty of moments like this when Seb could do it. Could do it while Moto slept. While he ate. Seb had half a mind to do it right now.
Moto said, “I count fifty-four of them. Give or take.”
“Fifty-four’s more’n a few,” said Seb.
“And fifty-four is exactly how many Elrahet said there’d be—though there is an odd fix about them.”
“An odd fix?”
Moto squinted again. He was having trouble keeping his quarry in focus.
“It’s like they’re…well…they’re a standard caravan guard, but it looks like they’re marching in squares.”
Seb didn’t know much, but she knew one thing for certain—Moto’s expectations were getting in the way of the truth. And there was one other thing she knew for certain. “There ain’t no caravan guard that keeps in squares,” she said.
“That’s why I say it’s an odd fix.”
“It’s an odd fix ‘cause they ain’t no caravan guard. They’re real fighting men. Elrahet was wrong.”
“Eight wagons, too. That exactly matches her premonitions.” 
Seb screwed up her face in thought. Eight wagons was several more than the average merchant train. Predicted, maybe, but a merchant guard marching in tight formation? Caravan hands in this part of the Sand were ragged bands of backwash from Hrkan conquests, not the kind to march in squares.
Those men out there were Skulsi, Seb was sure. Fifty-four Skulsi and a god-damned Mazid were bearing down on them. And how many more men might be hiding in those wagons? Thirty?
Seb compared all this to what the Ayramun brought to bear—forty-three bows. Forty-three bows and Ayram. And old Elrahet. Against anyone else she liked the odds, but nobody tangled with the Mazidai with good reason—the fire those slaves hid in their stomachs could wipe out entire armies.
But the Junei hills were a decent place to bushwhack a column of Hrks. Everywhere the slopes were steep, and no matter which particular route was taken into the pass there were places where strong shoulders would have a clean shot at the whole enemy column—that’s assuming the whole column was dumb and tried to stuff through all at once. Skulsi weren’t dumb. Against fearful men, an ambush here would be a slaughter. Against experienced warriors, Seb was not so sure. Add a Mazid…well if the Mazid was caught unawares...maybe the odds were three to one against. And that’s assuming the Mazid got taken down early and without too much trouble. 
 “I’d take them for Skulsi,” Moto said, “But even from here you can see they’re wearing that stingy brown wool of blackwood guards.”
“Could be common hands,” Seb replied.
“It could be.”
“Also could be those are Hrkan troops.”
“But they’re wrapped in brown wool.”
“So? A man can change his clothes.”
“A Skulsi doesn’t drop his whites for convenience, not even for subterfuge. It’d be a black mark.”
“The Sand makes converts of us all.”
Moto let go of his lens and watched them dangle on their chain. “Pride,” Moto noted through a plaintive sigh, “Is the only thing a Skulsi has. Once a soldier earns the whites, he’s not going to take them off for anything.” He paused. A subtle frown played on his lips. “Still, even if they’re wearing brown, they could be fighting men.”
“So they could be rabble, and they could be Skulsi.” 
“Skulsi won’t run when the killing starts.”
Seb nodded, and added, “And the way we’re set up—”
“I know. This only works if they try to run. But this is a game of risk. In the end, this is a Mazid we’re trying to catch. The Skulsi hardly matter.” 
“Then it’s decided,” Seb said. “It’s off.”
“That’s not for you to call, Seb. Sol’s light knows you’d be the last person allowed to make that call.”
“You ain’t shit either.”
“That’s where you’re wrong. Ayram put me in charge.”
Moto stood back up to make sure Seb got the full measure of him. “And like it or not, this is the only opportunity we’ll have to catch us a Mazid and its Minder. Elrahet being wrong about who they’re marching with isn’t enough to call this off.”
“What about the bones?”
“What about them?”
“If this don’t work out, an’ Ayram finds out there’s a dead body you didn’t let him know about it, then I’m blamin’ you. It’ll be your fault—your fault.”
“Yes, that’s how responsibility works.”
Moto then pinched a flat stone finger whistle between his lips and whistled the song of the Jek Tresset to let the Ayramun hidden in the valleys below know that the ambush was on. He stabbed and fluttered the high notes to encourage haste. Twittered replies sprang up from the hills below, and then, without so much as a parting nod, Moto set off down the path that led into that maze of mounded clay and rock.
Seb had different ideas about what she needed to do. She was going to run off to Elrahet’s cave, for the old witch was soon to conjure a blanket of fog the likes of which the Junei hills hadn’t seen for an age—a nice impenetrable fog to lay cover for the ambush, and damn it all if Seb didn’t get to watch how she did it.
Elrahet, Seb had learned, was difficult to track on account of the woman’s witchy senses. She couldn’t be followed. Seb only knew where her cave was because she’d scouted for it the night before—it was a thin crack in the base of a giant sloping slab of granite that constituted the greater part of a mountain peak. It was a bit of a climb to get to it. How Elrahet managed it, Seb had no idea.
When she made it to the cave crack, she could hear Elrahet’s faint mumblings echoing out. She shuffled inside and saw the old witch squatting over the corpse of a sizable black-backed lizard, both of them illuminated by a shaft of bluish light which poured down from a hole in the ceiling.
The lizard was belly up, and Elrahet’s fingers were already knuckle deep in its guts. Her arm twisted and twirled, and her lips whispered incantations as her upturned eyes searched the blue sliver of midday sky that peeked through the crack in the rock above.
Then she turned and set her dark eyes on Seb.
Seb stumbled backwards in fright and bumped her head on a rock and howled in pain.
“Damn!”
 Elrahet grimaced and spat at this interruption, then she set her eyes back on the sky, and put her hand to work again in the lizard’s corpse.
She lowered her voice to a whisper
Seb strained to hear her garbled words.
“Em bestet buguul.”
When the words were echoed and gone, Elrahet looked down at her handiwork and said, “Em bestet shemuul.” 
She pushed down hard with her palm to squeeze the last meal out from the lizard’s stomach. 
“Shefre gor, amkukre dor.” 
Her knotted fingers kneaded the intestines. 
“Shefre gor, zomgagor.”
 She ripped the entrails out of their webbed lining, and raised them up into the air and croaked, “We would be dust without it!” 
She dropped the entrails back into the body cavity, then stared intently at whatever was going on within.
Seb waited with bated breath for a sight of a Spark, or some effervescent swirl of glowing smoke, or anything, but nothing happened.
Elrahet snarled an arcane curse and tore the gash in the lizard’s white belly wider. Into this gaping hole she stuck her skinny arm up to the elbow, and with it she pushed the beast’s innards around in pursuit of something in its groin. The lizard’s belly bulged and squirmed. Once or twice its limbs twitched and its tail curled. Its gummy tongue popped out of its shovel mouth, and right when Seb supposed that the thing had come back to life,  Elrahet pulled her arm free and sat back with a defeated sigh.
“It is possible,” she said in a whisper loud enough for Seb to hear, “that the beast is infertile.”
Seb ventured nearer.
“This won’t work?” she asked as he knelt across from the witch.
“Not with this beast.”
Seb poked the lizard’s corpse with a curious finger. She could sense a power coming from the gaping hole in its belly. The blue-gray intestines inside writhed and pulsed like a twisted mass of worms.
“What are you gonna do?” she asked.
Elrahet hissed at her impudence, then said, “I need a fertile stomach.”
She looked at Seb’s stomach.
“Fresh blood from a fertile stomach,” she said.
Seb’s skin went cold at the insinuation.
“You are right here, in my cave, during my time of need. Did Solraheen provide you to me without my seeking?”
“My blood’s no good.”
“Quit your bellyaching and give me your arm.”
“My arm?”
“Your arm.”
“Thought you were gonna cut my stomach. How much blood you need?”
Blood was a sacred thing and it was never lightly given, least of all for magic. There’s no telling what a witch might do with it. But this was a golden chance to get in with the witch, and Seb had to take it. She studied Elrahet’s countenance to gauge her sincerity. Even in direct light, the difference between Elrahet’s smile and her frown was almost imperceptible under her sneer. It was common belief amongst the Ayramun that Elrahet never smiled at all, but Seb knew that wasn’t true. She’d seen her smile. She knew what it looked like. Elrahet wasn’t smiling now. 
“Your arm,” Elrahet said.
Seb rolled up her sleeve and extended her arm. Elrahet grabbed her wrist and Seb nearly wretched because Elrahet’s fingers were still dripping with the lizard’s blood, and she also didn’t care for the way Elrahet seemed to relish the sight of her veins bulging under her brown skin. And she didn’t like the way Elrahet smiled as she felt Seb shudder in her grip. Yes, she smiled. It caught Seb off-guard, for it was more than a crick in the corner of the lip, it was a full-on, nearly toothless grin.
Seb asked again, with more than a hint of unease, “How much do you need?” 
Elrahet’s smile faded and that mess of aged lines settled back into her familiar sneer. She pulled a yard of linen and a clay bowl from out of the shadows beside her and laid them between herself and Seb. Then she unsheathed a thin, curved golden knife from some hidden compartment in her robes and held its curve length-wise along Seb’s wrist.
“I value your trust,” she said, without affection.
“Do it.” 
Elrahet savored the lack of courtesy, then pricked her dagger’s tip into Seb’s flesh and flicked her wrist with expert care to open the vein. Seb remained stoic through the sting but she watched with grave concern as blood streamed out of the wound and ran around her wrist and over Elrahet’s knuckles as it flowed steadily down into the bowl.
After what seemed an eternity, she jerked her arm free. 
“That’s it,” she said firmly, and she held her hand up and pinched the wound closed with her thumb.
“Your gift is humbling,” said Elrahet, “But the bowl is half-full.”
“That should be enough.”
“Is it?”
“A poor witch blames her tools.”
Elrahet scowled. “Who told you that?”
“You’re not the only witch I’ve known.”
Elrahet grumbled as if she were about to bark and bite. 
Seb backed away.
When next Elrahet spoke her voice was thick with contempt. 
“Think worse of where you sit on the scales of mercy. I could have your stomach for a bag.”
She tossed the scrap of linen at Seb’s face and shooed her out with a flick of her finger.
Seb cursed herself yet again, because not only did she spoil whatever goodwill she thought she’d earned, but she’d let Elrahet prick the wrong wrist, her pulling wrist. Every pull of the bowstring in the coming ambush would bring a twinge of pain. </Text>
