            <Title>Quick!</Title>
            <Text>The moment was perfect.
Lorba Bargu had her nice, cozy rocking chair she’d built out of a bent and sanded gabbu tree she grew from a seed. She had her nice, heavy blue blanket that her loving husband Kam had knit out of the softest wool. The silver sky was pleasant, with the rain tap-tapping on the clay-shingles of her master’s wagon house, which was better described as a sheltered porch adjoining her master’s western wall. It was not a grand shelter, though it offered a grand view, advantaged, as it was, at the top of Meskalim's central hill looking west, with the sprawling mud-city spread out below and the foggy, Shalbrum Sea boiling beyond it.
The moment’s only discordant note was her blistered heels, for she was still wearing in the stiff leather boots made two days before by her son, who was a cobbler’s apprentice. This slight pain was a beauty mark, an ugliness which when juxtaposed against perfection enhanced it.
Yes, the moment was perfect.
Almost perfect.
Unfortunately, her wagon’s bed was full-up with the half-dead bodies of artists. She knew they were artists, because when her master carried them out of the great house they had paint on their fingers and clothes, usually black paint. And she knew they were only half-dead instead of full-dead, because after killing them, her master brought them out to her wagon house to administer a rainbow potion which, he claimed, ‘stabilized the Spark’. Her master kept this potion hidden in a false drawer in her workbench. Lorba never touched this hidden treasure. She wanted nothing to do with it. She only ever watched when her master would force a few drops of that shimmering liquid down into the corpse’s mouth, and she didn’t help when he sat the the poor wretches up and shook them to make sure the liquid was running fast down into the stomach. To her, this habit of her master’s was an eccentricity she could forgive for the sake of the job, for the sake of these moments where she could sit high up, rock back-and-forth, and feel comfortable, secure, even delight at how her life had turned out.

“You think his Spark has faded?”
Salavan shook his fat head. He nodded towards the wagon and said, “Stuff him in with the others.”


