            <Title>BURGEONSCRATCH</Title>
            <Text> in the shadow of the tower, was Ayram and Elrahet, and further out, prancing on the glowing red-orange sand was the white horse and it’s grey-robed rider, who cradled a black-robed child.

Flowing out of them all was goldness, purpose made maniefst, and this goldness was swimming under the sand, churning in the tower’s shadow and breathing out the tower itself. It sparkled the stone of the window-sill under Mandri’s fingers


The figures below were stuck in dynamic, limb-bent postures, seemingly fixed by the golden thread into a golden pyramidal frame—Ayram and Elrahet anchored bottom corners, the scribe on his white horse towered into a point. This was true purpose here, not to be mistaken for mere symbolism, no, the scribe, he did not represent Hrkan power advantaged on a proud steed, he was that power, and in his lap was the Riga child, the very embodiment of Hrk’s assault on the sanctity of creation. Ayram was not a symbol of the outland peoples, he was their paragon, and standing next to him was Elrahet, who was herself the very essence of the Sand given agency. Lying on the ground, woven into the middle of this golden triangle, was the Mazyd Obo, a creature constructed for the sole purpose of setting the affairs of humanity in order, and look where he was, destitute in the dirt, scarred and cowering and naked. The others looked past him as if he weren’t there at all.

He was forced instead imprint the scene upon his mind as best he could. He kept his eye jumping from detail to detail and back again, and then back again, and again, and again, and at each stop he beheld the object, an act beyond mere noticing—this was the artist's noticing, the lover's noticing, covetous noticing, jealous noticing, noticing to remember—beholding not a lossless art, but what gets lost has chance of being reconstructed later.

He ran through it all like a shopping list.
The arc of the tower’s shadow splitting the scene in half. 
The coolness of color inside that shadow and its subtle, sumptuous greys, almost looking blue.
The size disparity between Ayram and Elrahet—both dark and shrouded in that tower’s shadow. 
The Hrkan horse, Sol’s light, what a specimen—white as chalk. It’s brushed muscles glistened in the light of the sun. It’s neck as wide as Ayram’s shoulders. It’s eyes were as wide as a scream. It’s tail, impatient, was richly braided.
Sitting in the brown saddle was the Hrkan scribe, his dark skin reddened and glistening with kell oil. The trail of his grey robe was filigreed with golden leaves. His right arm cradled the black-bundled Riga with care. 
Obo on the ground. Pale. Fly-swatted. Staring at the sky. So perfect was the staging that the warm spectral edge of the tower's penumbra cut right across his stomach. 
The rest of the world—the tower bricks, the mush of rock and sand—these were static things and could be ignored because they could be revisited later. It was an injustice, abstracting them out as if they weren't bound by the golden thread and contributing to the moment’s purpose, but Mandri knew it was more than he could manage.
He ran through the details again. 
The arc of the tower’s shadow—that hadn't changed.
Ayram and Elrahet still stood resolute.
The horse hadn’t even shifted it’s weight. It’d been standing on two feet this whole time. Wonderful. 

He noticed a new detail—the white line of Hrkan soldiers hanging in the distance. It would take a large canvas to accommodate them. A lot of paint. He twinged at the thought having to fill up so large a frame.

Should he include the golden light of purpose? How to paint it? It wasn’t as simple as a shaft of light or an ephemeral back-lit rim of gold, it was more like a pulsing mist, and yet, not like a mist at all.
He would have to worry about that later. The details need accounting.
A new detail—Ayram’s spear—how had he missed it? , for the dark tip of that spear formed an unsightly tangent with the horse’s dark leather stirrup, such that the stirrup and accompanying harness seemed to sprout out from the haft. This element would need to be fixed. It flattened the image. Mandri could adjust the angle of the bar in Ayram’s hand so that it needn’t intersect with the stirrup at all.
Would it be sacrilegious to alter this image in any way?
Was the angle of the spear part of the purpose?
Did he miss anything?

Mandri wished there wasn’t there, because a vulture circling the scene was almost too on the nose. People might start to think that this was all his own doing. Maybe he should remove the vulture.
</Text>
